c2c48de5-f91b-442b-9807-0131a866dfa1	2026-05-19 09:16:00.347102	\N	\N	329933	8727377d-719d-4f54-9dc9-d02329ac7665	Adopting Biome Toolchain for Next.js Project\n\n1. Executive Summary\n\nThis document proposes replacing our current linting and formatting stack (ESLint +\nPrettier) with Biome for the upcoming Next.js project. Biome is a Rust-based toolchain that\nunifies linting, formatting, and import sorting. Benchmarks and case studies indicate\nBiome is 20x–25x faster than the traditional stack, significantly reducing CI/CD times and\nimproving developer experience (DX). While Biome has a smaller plugin ecosystem, its\nrecent v2.0 updates regarding type-aware linting and GritQL plugins make it a viable, high-\nperformance alternative for modern web development.\n\n2. Problem Statement: The Friction of ESLint + Prettier\n\nWhile ESLint and Prettier are industry standards, they introduce significant overhead in a\nmodern Next.js environment:\n\nCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\f• Performance Bottlenecks: ESLint is Node.js-based and slow. Linting a medium-to-large\ncodebase can take 28+ seconds, whereas Biome can process it in ~1.3 seconds. This\nlatency discourages running linters locally or slows down git hooks.\n\n• Configuration Hell: A typical setup requires managing multiple config files (.eslintrc,\n.prettierrc, .eslintignore) and 10–50+ dev dependencies (e.g., eslint-config-prettier, eslint-\nplugin-react, eslint-plugin-import) to prevent conflicts between the linter and formatter.\n\n• Slow CI/CD: Heavy linting steps increase build times and costs in CI pipelines.\n\n3. Proposed Solution: Biome\n\nBiome is a performant toolchain built in Rust that provides a linter, formatter, and import\nsorter in a single binary.\n\n• Unified Tooling: Formatting, linting, and import sorting happen in one pass.\n\n• Zero-Config Philosophy: It works out of the box with sensible defaults for TypeScript,\nJSX, and JSON, requiring minimal setup.\n\n• High Compatibility: The formatter is ~97% compatible with Prettier, making migration\nseamless.\n\n4. Detailed Analysis: Biome vs. ESLint + Prettier\n\n4.1. Extreme Performance (Rust-Based)\n\n•  Speed: Biome is approximately 25x faster than Prettier for formatting and 15x-20x\n\n•\n\nfaster than ESLint for linting.\nImpact: A full codebase check that takes 30s with ESLint might take <2s with\nBiome. This enables instant feedback loops and allows running the full linter on\nevery file save or commit without lag.\n\nTable 4.1: Comparison of Linting and Formatting Processing Time\n\nCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\fTest Scenario\n\nTool\n\nProcessing\nTime\n\nRelative\nSpeed\n\nReference\n\nSmall Project (Next.js, 45\nfiles)\n\nESLint +\nPrettier\n\n3.2 seconds\n\n1x\n\nMedium Project (180 files)\n\nBiome\n\n0.4 seconds\n\nESLint +\nPrettier\n\n12.8 seconds\n\n8x\n\n1x\n\nBiome\n\n1.1 seconds\n\n11.6x\n\nLarge Project (Monorepo,\n2000+ files)\n\nESLint +\nPrettier\n\n~40–60\nseconds\n\n1x\n\nBiome\n\n~2–3 seconds\n\n~20x\n\nLinting 100k lines of code\n\nESLint\n\n15–30 seconds  1x\n\nBiome\n\n~200 ms\n\n~75x\n\nObservation:\nThe performance improvement is not linear but exponential relative to project size. As\nproject scale increases, Biome’s advantages become increasingly significant due to its\nhighly scalable multi-threaded architecture.\n\nRef: 1, 2\n\n4.2. Unified & Simplified Architecture\n\n•  Single Dependency: Replaces dozens of packages (eslint, prettier, eslint-plugin-*)\n\nwith one package: biomejs/biome.\n\n•  Single Config: Configuration is centralized in biome.json, eliminating the "config\n\nhell" of managing conflicting rules between linters and formatters.\n\n•  Built-in Import Sorting: Biome organizes imports automatically (similar to eslint-\n\nplugin-import but faster and built-in).\n\n4.3. Advanced Features & DX\n\n•  VCS Integration: Biome natively integrates with git to process only changed files,\n\nremoving the need for external tools like lint-staged,.\n\n•  Helpful Diagnostics: Error messages are designed to be actionable and often\n\ninclude context or fix suggestions, superior to generic ESLint errors.\n\nCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\f•  Monorepo Support: In monorepo projects (using Nx, Turborepo), ESLint often faces\nperformance issues because it has to load hundreds of nested package.json and\n.eslintrc files. Biome supports a nested configuration model and can automatically\ndetect workspaces more efficiently.\n\n5. Cons & Limitations\n\n5.1 Ecosystem & Plugins (GritQL)\n\nThis is Biome’s biggest weakness compared to ESLint.\n\n•  No support for ESLint plugins: Biome cannot run ESLint plugins. ESLint has a\nmassive ecosystem with over 1,000 plugins (such as eslint-plugin-react, eslint-\nplugin-jsx-a11y, eslint-plugin-import, etc.). In contrast, Biome only provides around\n420+ built-in rules.\n\n•  Lack of niche rules: If your project heavily depends on advanced security rules (e.g.\n\neslint-plugin-security) or highly framework-specific rules (for example, image\noptimization rules in eslint-config-next), Biome currently does not support these.\n\n•  Difficulty in writing custom rules: Previously, Biome did not support custom rules\nat all. Since version 2.0, Biome has introduced plugin support via GritQL. However,\nwriting rules in GritQL has a much steeper learning curve than writing rules in\nJavaScript for ESLint, and the GritQL community and ecosystem are still very small.\n\nCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\fCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\f5.2 Strict Type Checking Gap\n\n•  Limitation: Biome's type inference is optimized for speed and covers about 85% of what\ntypescript-eslint catches. It does not replace the full strictness of the TypeScript\ncompiler,.\n\n•  Mitigation: We rely on tsc (TypeScript Compiler) for strict type checking during the\n\nbuild process, using Biome primarily for fast dev-loop feedback.\n\n5.3 Support for frameworks beyond React\n\nIf your project expands to frameworks other than React/Next.js:\n\n•  Vue, Svelte, Astro: Biome v2.3 has started to support .vue, .svelte, and .astro files,\nbut this support is still experimental or not as mature as ESLint. For example, linting\nrules may not work reliably across the HTML/CSS/JS sections within a .vue file.\n\n•  Angular: Support for Angular is still very limited compared to ESLint’s rich and well-\n\nestablished ecosystem.\n\nTable: Biome vs. ESLint + Prettier\n\nCriteria\n\nBiome\n\nESLint + Prettier\n\nArchitecture\n\nUnified toolchain: Built-in Linter,\nFormatter, and Import Sorter in a\nsingle tool written in Rust.\n\nFragmented: Requires two\nseparate tools. ESLint handles\nlinting, Prettier handles\nformatting. Import sorting\nneeds additional plugins.\n\nPerformance\n\nBlazing fast: ~25× faster than\nPrettier (formatting) and ~15–20×\nfaster than ESLint (linting). Can\nlint/format large projects in\nseconds.\n\nSlower: Runs on Node.js.\nExecution time increases\nsignificantly with project size\n(e.g., 28s+ for 300 files vs.\n~1.3s with Biome).\n\nConfiguration\n\nSimple (zero-config): Only one\nbiome.json file. Minimal complexity;\nsetup takes minutes.\n\nDependencies  Minimal: Install a single package\n\n(@biomejs/biome).\n\nComplex (config hell):\nMultiple config files (.eslintrc,\n.prettierrc, .eslintignore) and\nextra setup to avoid conflicts\nbetween tools.\n\nHeavy: Requires 10–50+\npackages (eslint, prettier,\nplugins, configs, parsers, etc.).\n\nCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\fEcosystem\n\nType-Aware\nLinting\n\nLimited: ~200+ built-in rules. No\nESLint plugin support. New plugin\nsystem (GritQL) is in beta and has a\nsteep learning curve.\n\nMassive: 10+ years of\ndevelopment with thousands\nof plugins supporting nearly all\nframeworks and niche needs\n(security, advanced a11y, etc.).\n\nFast & “good enough”: Uses an\ninternal inference engine, no\nTypeScript Compiler (TSC) required.\nCatches ~85% of type issues with\nvery high speed.\n\nHighly accurate but slow:\nUses typescript-eslint powered\nby TSC. Extremely powerful but\nsignificantly slows down\nlinting.\n\nImport Sorting\n\nBuilt-in: Automatically sorts and\noptimizes imports without extra\nsetup.\n\nPlugin required: Needs eslint-\nplugin-import or additional\nPrettier configuration.\n\nCI/CD & Git\nIntegration\n\nNative: Built-in support for linting\nonly changed files based on Git, no\nlint-staged required.\n\nMonorepo\nSupport\n\nFirst-class: Supports nested configs\nand workspaces smoothly since\nv2.0.\n\nRequires extra tools:\nCommonly combined with lint-\nstaged and husky for CI\nperformance optimization.\n\nCascading configs:\nSupported, but config\ninheritance in monorepos is\noften complex to manage.\n\nCompatibility\nLevel\n\nHigh (97%): ~97% compatible with\nPrettier. Provides migration tools\nfrom ESLint/Prettier to Biome.\n\nIndustry standard: The current\ngold standard; compatible with\nall IDEs and legacy toolchains.\n\n6. Recommendation\n\nFor the upcoming Next.js project, Biome is the recommended choice. The introduction of\nmonorepo support and fast type-aware linting in v2.0 solves the major blockers that\npreviously existed. The 20x performance gain and reduced configuration maintenance\nsignificantly outweighs the trade-off of a smaller plugin ecosystem.\n\nCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\fReferences:\n\nhttps://www.reddit.com/r/typescript/comments/1ldwrxr/biome_v2_ships_typeaware_rules\n_without_the_ts/\n\nhttps://betterstack.com/community/guides/scaling-nodejs/biome-eslint/\n\nhttps://freedium-mirror.cfd/https://medium.com/navara/biome-the-faster-lint-and-\nformatting-alternative-to-prettier-12fcf8b122b9\n\nhttps://kittygiraudel.com/2024/06/01/from-eslint-and-prettier-to-biome/\n\nhttps://www.ekino.fr/publications/is-biome-ready-to-replace-prettier-eslint/\n\nhttps://dev.to/saswatapal/why-i-chose-biome-over-eslintprettier-20x-faster-linting-one-\ntool-to-rule-them-all-10kf\n\nhttps://www.amillionmonkeys.co.uk/blog/biome-vs-eslint-prettier\n\nhttps://dev.to/nqhed/biome-a-good-tool-for-linting-and-formatting-code-4g4j\n\nhttps://github.com/biomejs/biome/blob/main/benchmark/README.md\n\nhttps://biomejs.dev/internals/language-support/\n\nCopyright © 2026 VATECH Networks | All Rights Reserved. / Confidential\n\n\n	application/pdf	global/8727377d-719d-4f54-9dc9-d02329ac7665/original.pdf	GPP Biome Adoption Proposal.pdf	\N	INGESTED	GPP Biome Adoption Proposal	2026-05-19 09:16:48.762	kn8Or94GjDWRK8mlzWJuY65sRqjvmnkz
